You'll declare a `priority_queue` in the first 30 seconds of every heap problem, so these four declarations need to be muscle memory:

```cpp
#include <queue>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

// MAX-heap (default): top() is the LARGEST element
priority_queue<int> maxHeap;

// MIN-heap: top() is the SMALLEST element. Memorize this incantation.
priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> minHeap;

// Heap of pairs — orders by .first, then .second (lexicographic).
// Min-heap of (cost, node) is the workhorse for Dijkstra / K-way merge.
priority_queue<pair<int,int>, vector<pair<int,int>>, greater<pair<int,int>>> pq;

// Custom comparator via lambda (e.g. order points by distance to origin).
// NOTE: the comparator returns true when a should come BELOW b (weaker priority),
// which is the REVERSE of the intuition — same rule as sort's comparator inverted.
auto cmp = [](const vector<int>& a, const vector<int>& b) {
    return a[0]*a[0]+a[1]*a[1] > b[0]*b[0]+b[1]*b[1]; // '>' => min-heap by distance
};
priority_queue<vector<int>, vector<vector<int>>, decltype(cmp)> distHeap(cmp);
```

> [!PITFALL] The default is a MAX-heap
> This is *the* most common C++ heap bug, and it fails silently — your code compiles, runs, and returns wrong answers. If you want the smallest on top, you must write the full three-argument form with `greater<int>`. Say it out loud when you declare it: "min-heap, so `greater`."

> [!WARNING] Comparator direction is inverted vs `sort`
> For a heap, the comparator returning `true` means "`a` has *lower* priority than `b`" — `a` sinks toward the bottom. So `>` in the comparator produces a **min**-heap. When in doubt, don't argue with yourself: push 3 elements, print `top()`, and check.

> [!NOTE]
> The pair form `priority_queue<pair<int,int>, ..., greater<...>>` compares by `.first` then `.second`. Put the sort key first — `(cost, node)`, `(value, listIndex)` — and everything just works. This exact declaration returns in Week 6 as the engine of Dijkstra.

Here's the counter-intuitive move that unlocks the whole top-K family: to find the K **largest** elements, keep a **min-heap capped at size K**.

> [!INTUITION] Guard the door with your weakest champion
> Imagine a club that only admits the K largest numbers seen so far. The bouncer doesn't need to know the whole ranking — only the *weakest current member*, because that's who a newcomer must beat to get in. A min-heap of the champions puts exactly that weakest member at `top()`, so every admission decision is one comparison plus one $O(\log K)$ swap.

[[fig:m08-topk-evict]]

Stream every element through; if the heap grows past K, pop — the pop always removes the smallest, i.e. the one that just lost its seat:

```cpp
// Returns the K largest elements (unordered).
vector<int> topKLargest(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> minHeap; // min-heap, cap = k
    for (int x : nums) {
        minHeap.push(x);
        if ((int)minHeap.size() > k) minHeap.pop(); // drop the current smallest
    }
    vector<int> res;
    while (!minHeap.empty()) { res.push_back(minHeap.top()); minHeap.pop(); }
    return res; // the k survivors are the k largest
}
```

This runs in $O(n \log k)$ with $O(k)$ extra space — a real win over the $O(n \log n)$ full sort when $k \ll n$. The mirror image works too: K **smallest** → size-K **max**-heap.

> [!EXAM]
> When a Codility/Flipkart problem says "top K" and $n$ is huge, they are testing whether you know $O(n \log k)$. In an interview, narrate all three tiers: full sort $O(n \log n)$, heap $O(n \log k)$, quickselect $O(n)$ average — then implement the heap version because it's short and safe under time pressure.

You have $k$ sorted lists and want one merged output (or just the K-th smallest overall). Concatenating and sorting is $O(N \log N)$ over all $N$ elements and throws away the sortedness you were given.

The observation that saves you: at any moment, the global next-smallest element **must be one of the $k$ current heads** — the first unconsumed element of each list. Everything deeper is blocked behind its own head. So you never need $N$ candidates in play, only $k$:

[[fig:m08-kway]]

Seed the heap with one entry per list. Each entry carries enough info to find its successor. Pop the global min, emit it, push its successor from the *same* list:

```cpp
// Merge k sorted vectors. Heap holds (value, whichList, indexInThatList).
vector<int> mergeK(vector<vector<int>>& lists) {
    priority_queue<array<int,3>, vector<array<int,3>>, greater<array<int,3>>> pq;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)lists.size(); ++i)
        if (!lists[i].empty()) pq.push({lists[i][0], i, 0});
    vector<int> res;
    while (!pq.empty()) {
        auto [val, li, idx] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        res.push_back(val);
        if (idx + 1 < (int)lists[li].size())
            pq.push({lists[li][idx+1], li, idx+1}); // push successor from same list
    }
    return res;
}
```

> [!KEY]
> The heap never exceeds size $k$: you seed $k$ entries and every pop is followed by *at most one* push. Invariant: **at most one live head per list**. That caps every operation at $O(\log k)$, so the whole merge is $O(N \log k)$ time, $O(k)$ space — and it *streams*, so you can stop early after emitting the first M elements.

This one skeleton, re-skinned, solves **Merge k Sorted Lists**, **Kth Smallest in a Sorted Matrix** (seed the first column, push the right/down neighbor), and **Find K Pairs with Smallest Sums** (seed `(nums1[i], nums2[0])` pairs, lazily push neighbors).

deepdives.answer:
**Why the naive approaches fail.** A sorted array gives $O(1)$ median but every insert is $O(n)$ — you shift elements to make room. A balanced BST works but is a lot of code and easy to get wrong under time pressure. Neither exploits the key fact: **you never need the full order — only the middle.**

> [!INTUITION]
> The median only cares about the *boundary* between the smaller half and the larger half of the data. So maintain exactly that boundary and nothing more: a max-heap `lo` whose top is the largest of the small numbers (the left side of the median), and a min-heap `hi` whose top is the smallest of the large numbers (the right side).

[[fig:m08-two-heaps]]

Keep them balanced — `lo` has the same count as `hi`, or exactly one more — and the median is `lo.top()` when the total is odd, or the average of the two tops when even.

**The trick that makes insertion correct.** The subtle bug is deciding which half a new number belongs to without hand-writing boundary comparisons (which explode into empty-heap edge cases). Instead, launder it through both heaps:

```cpp
lo.push(num);                 // 1) blindly add to the smaller half
hi.push(lo.top()); lo.pop();  // 2) shove lo's current max into hi
                              //    -> guarantees every lo element <= every hi element
if (hi.size() > lo.size()) {  // 3) if hi got too big, hand its min back to lo
    lo.push(hi.top()); hi.pop();
}
```

Step 2 is the elegant part: you let `num` enter `lo` unconditionally, then push `lo`'s maximum across. That maximum is *exactly* the element that should sit on the boundary — whether it's `num` itself or an older element `num` displaced — so the ordering invariant $\max(lo) \le \min(hi)$ repairs itself automatically. Step 3 only fixes sizes, never ordering.

```cpp
priority_queue<int> lo;                                     // max-heap: smaller half
priority_queue<int, vector<int>, greater<int>> hi;         // min-heap: larger half

void addNum(int num) {
    lo.push(num);
    hi.push(lo.top()); lo.pop();
    if (hi.size() > lo.size()) { lo.push(hi.top()); hi.pop(); }
}
double findMedian() {
    return lo.size() > hi.size() ? lo.top() : (lo.top() + hi.top()) / 2.0;
}
```

**Complexity:** each `addNum` is $O(\log n)$; `findMedian` is $O(1)$; space $O(n)$. This is the intended solution and interviewers expect it *by name* — "two heaps."

**Follow-up they love:** if all numbers are known to lie in $[0, 100]$, replace the heaps with a 101-bucket count array and answer in $O(100)$ per query. Mention it — it shows range awareness, and the same downgrade applies to any small-domain order statistic.

**Why greedy-by-most-frequent is right.** The task with the highest remaining count is the bottleneck — it's the one that forces idle gaps. So in every scheduling window you want the most-frequent *still-remaining* tasks placed first, spaced out by the cooldown. A **max-heap keyed on remaining count** hands you the current most-frequent task in $O(\log 26)$.

**The algorithm, step by step.** Process time in rounds of length `n+1` — exactly one cooldown window, the shortest span in which a task can legally repeat. In each round: pop up to `n+1` *distinct* tasks from the heap (they're all different, so no cooldown conflicts inside the window), decrement each, stash the survivors, and push them back after the round.

[[fig:m08-task-windows]]

```cpp
int leastInterval(vector<char>& tasks, int n) {
    int cnt[26] = {0};
    for (char c : tasks) cnt[c - 'A']++;
    priority_queue<int> pq;                 // max-heap of remaining counts
    for (int c : cnt) if (c) pq.push(c);

    int time = 0;
    while (!pq.empty()) {
        vector<int> temp;                   // tasks scheduled this window
        for (int i = 0; i < n + 1; ++i) {   // one cooldown window = n+1 slots
            if (!pq.empty()) { temp.push_back(pq.top() - 1); pq.pop(); }
        }
        for (int r : temp) if (r > 0) pq.push(r); // re-arm tasks that remain
        // if heap emptied out, the last partial window has no trailing idle
        time += pq.empty() ? (int)temp.size() : n + 1;
    }
    return time;
}
```

> [!PITFALL] The one gotcha is the final window
> In every *full* window you charge `n + 1` slots even if you placed fewer than `n+1` real tasks — the remainder are forced idles. But in the **last** window (heap empty afterwards) there is nothing left to wait for, so you charge only `temp.size()`, the real tasks you actually placed. Getting that boundary right is the whole problem.

**Complexity:** $O(T)$ total heap operations over all tasks, each $O(\log 26) = O(1)$ effectively — so linear. There's also a slick $O(1)$ closed-form counting formula, but the heap version is what *generalizes* (it adapts when tasks gain priorities, arrival times, or per-task cooldowns) and it's what you should lead with.

**Why not just concatenate and sort?** That's $O(N \log N)$ over all $N$ nodes and throws away the fact that each list is *already sorted*. The heap version is $O(N \log k)$ — a real win when $k$ is small relative to $N$ — and it streams: you can stop early after emitting the first M elements.

> [!KEY]
> At any moment the global next-smallest node is the minimum among the **current heads** of the k lists — only k candidates, never N. A size-k min-heap tracks exactly those heads. Pop the min, splice it onto the result, and push that node's `next` to refill its list's slot.

[[fig:m08-kway]]

```cpp
struct Cmp { bool operator()(ListNode* a, ListNode* b){ return a->val > b->val; } };

ListNode* mergeKLists(vector<ListNode*>& lists) {
    priority_queue<ListNode*, vector<ListNode*>, Cmp> pq;
    for (auto l : lists) if (l) pq.push(l);   // seed with every non-empty head
    ListNode dummy, *tail = &dummy;
    while (!pq.empty()) {
        ListNode* node = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        tail->next = node; tail = node;       // splice smallest onto the result
        if (node->next) pq.push(node->next);  // refill from the SAME list
    }
    return dummy.next;
}
```

Two details worth narrating:

- The comparator uses `>` — remember, for a `priority_queue` that inversion is what produces a **min**-heap by `val`.
- **Why the heap never exceeds size k:** you seed k nodes, and every pop is followed by *at most one* push. The invariant "at most one live head per list" caps it, which is what makes each operation $O(\log k)$.

**Complexity:** $O(N \log k)$ time, $O(k)$ space (the dummy-head splice reuses existing nodes — no allocation).

**What generalizes:** the identical skeleton solves **Kth Smallest Element in a Sorted Matrix** (seed the first column; on pop, push the neighbor(s)) and **Find K Pairs with Smallest Sums** (seed `(nums1[i] + nums2[0])` pairs; lazily push the `j+1` neighbor). Any time sorted sources feed one consumer, think K-way merge.

**Why sorting alone fails.** You want the most profitable project — but *affordability changes as your capital grows*. A project too expensive now becomes reachable after a few wins. You need two different orderings live at the same time: by capital (to know what unlocks) and by profit (to know what to grab). One sort can't serve both.

> [!INTUITION] Unlock, then grab
> Run a pipeline: a **min-heap by capital** holds the locked projects with the cheapest-to-unlock on top, and it feeds a **max-heap by profit** holding everything currently affordable. Each round: drain every project whose capital requirement ≤ current capital across to the profit side, then pop the single richest available project and bank it.

(In the code below the "capital min-heap" is flattened into a capital-sorted array walked by an index `i` — same effect, less code.)

```cpp
int findMaximizedCapital(int k, int W, vector<int>& profits, vector<int>& capital) {
    int n = profits.size();
    vector<pair<int,int>> proj(n);           // (capital, profit)
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) proj[i] = {capital[i], profits[i]};
    sort(proj.begin(), proj.end());          // ascending by capital => easy unlocking
    priority_queue<int> avail;               // max-heap of unlocked profits
    int i = 0;
    while (k--) {
        while (i < n && proj[i].first <= W) avail.push(proj[i++].second);
        if (avail.empty()) break;            // nothing affordable => stop
        W += avail.top(); avail.pop();       // take the richest reachable project
    }
    return W;
}
```

**Why the greedy is safe.** Completing a project never *reduces* capital, so once something is affordable it stays affordable forever — unlocking is monotone, which is why the index `i` never needs to move backwards. Given that, taking the max-profit unlocked project each round is a standard exchange argument: swapping it for any lesser choice can only lower (or match) your capital at every future step.

**Complexity:** $O(n \log n)$ for the sort plus $O((n + k) \log n)$ heap traffic — call it $O(n \log n)$. 

**What generalizes:** this "monotone unlock stream feeds a max-heap, greedily extract" shape recurs across scheduling and resource problems — courses with deadlines, fuel stops, machine assignment. When a greedy needs *two orderings at once*, reach for two heaps.
